{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638030"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:48:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17685"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17685"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80674"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10481"},{"type":"tags","id":"10509"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24291"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80674"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Na-K-2Cl symporter in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle is responsible for ion transport across the renal tubular epithelium. This transport process requires energy to move ions against their concentration gradients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the energy source that drives the Na-K-2Cl symporter?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ATP hydrolysis via primary active transport","Sodium concentration gradient via secondary active transport","Potassium concentration gradient via secondary active transport","Chloride concentration gradient via secondary active transport","Calcium concentration gradient via secondary active transport"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Na-K-2Cl symporter uses the \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium concentration gradient \u003C/strong\u003Ethat is generated \u003Cstrong\u003Evia secondary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E. This sodium gradient is generated by the sodium-potassium ATPase on the basolateral membrane. This makes it a secondary active transport process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATP hydrolysis via primary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - The Na-K-2Cl symporter does not directly utilise ATP, but rather harnesses the energy stored in the sodium gradient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium concentration gradient via secondary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Although potassium is transported by the symporter, its concentration gradient is not the primary driving force for transport.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloride concentration gradient via secondary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - The chloride gradient is established as a consequence of the transport process rather than serving as its energy source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium concentration gradient via secondary active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium ions are not involved in this transport mechanism and their gradient does not contribute to its function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium gradient is maintained by the sodium-potassium ATPase, which uses ATP to pump sodium out of the cell. This gradient then provides the energy for the Na-K-2Cl symporter to move ions against their concentration gradients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Na-K-2Cl symporter in the thick ascending limb actively transports sodium, potassium and chloride ions from the tubular lumen into cells in a 1:1:2 ratio.","The Na-K-2Cl symporter requires energy from the sodium gradient established by the sodium-potassium ATPase."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17685"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65970"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T09:02:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T09:03:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10399"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80674"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links"